You have several options for financial support in your role as a caregiver.

### Financial support for rent, utilities, gas, and groceries 

DCYF may provide assistance with rent, utilities, or gas. Ask your child’s caseworker for help covering these costs as soon as possible. Once you become licensed, you’re no longer eligible for these sources of support. 

**Clothing vouchers**

DCYF may provide clothing vouchers for the child. Ask your child’s caseworker about these vouchers. 

### Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (TANF) 
Temporary Assistance for Needy Families (TANF) supports families with children experiencing low income. TANF is a cash assistance program administered by the Department of Social and Health Services (DSHS).

As a kinship caregiver, you may be eligible for [non-needy relative TANF](https://www.dshs.wa.gov/esa/community-services-offices/non-needy-relative-loco-parentis-and-legal-guardian-grant). It’s sometimes called “child-only” TANF because applications do not consider your income.  

{% Callout %}You may be asked about your income on the non-needy relative TANF application. This is to find out if you qualify for other benefits programs.{% endCallout %}  

DCYF encourages you to apply for non-needy relative TANF to get financial support during the licensing process.

